{"parse":{"title":"DIF (technique)","pageid":29978467,"revid":766248472,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p><b>DIF</b> is a <a href=\"/wiki/Greenhouse\" title=\"Greenhouse\">greenhouse</a> technique involving temperature control for the purpose of controlling plant <a href=\"/wiki/Plant_stem\" title=\"Plant stem\">internode</a> length and thus elongation rates. DIF's effectiveness has led to a reduction in the need and use of chemical <a href=\"/wiki/Plant_growth_regulators\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Plant growth regulators\">plant growth regulators</a>. Although many common greenhouse plants do react strongly to -DIF, there are some plants which show little or no response to -DIF.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Basics\">Basics</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=DIF_(technique)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Basics\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>DIF refers to the difference between daytime and nighttime temperatures. DIF is calculated by subtracting the nighttime temperature from the daytime temperature to get a +DIF when the daytime is warmer, or a -DIF when the night time is warmer. When there is a +DIF, elongation rates are normal, but when there is a -DIF elongation rates are lowered. As nights are generally cooler than days, the DIF technique is only actively utilized to slow growth, not to increase growth.\n</p><p>Instead of increasing heating all through the night, which can be very expensive, another approach to getting a -DIF response is to decrease the temperature in the greenhouse at dawn for 2-3hours. This temporary decrease in temperature from night to day tricks the plant into responding as if there was a -DIF. An optimal DIF is around -10 when measuring in Fahrenheit or approximately -6 in Celsius.<sup id=\"cite_ref-ref1_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-ref1-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Drawbacks\">Drawbacks</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=DIF_(technique)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Drawbacks\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>DIF treatments can also slow the <a href=\"/wiki/Growing_degree-day\" title=\"Growing degree-day\">development rate</a> when the average daytime temperature is decreased. Very high -DIFs can also led to problems such as <a href=\"/wiki/Chlorosis\" title=\"Chlorosis\">chlorosis</a> in <a href=\"/wiki/Lilium\" title=\"Lilium\">lilies</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-ref1_2-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-ref1-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=DIF_(technique)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Cox, Douglas (2007) <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://ag.umass.edu/greenhouse-floriculture/fact-sheets/controlling-plant-height-without-chemicals\">\"Controlling Plant Height Without Chemicals\"</a> Soil and Insect Sciences | University of Massachusetts Amherst</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-ref1-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-ref1_2-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-ref1_2-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external free\" href=\"http://hortservicesinc.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/What-is-DIF.pdf\">http://hortservicesinc.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/What-is-DIF.pdf</a></span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n\n<!-- \nNewPP limit report\nParsed by mw1256\nCached time: 20180912092638\nCache expiry: 1900800\nDynamic content: false\nCPU time usage: 0.028 seconds\nReal time usage: 0.036 seconds\nPreprocessor visited node count: 106/1000000\nPreprocessor generated node count: 0/1500000\nPost\u2010expand include size: 329/2097152 bytes\nTemplate argument size: 79/2097152 bytes\nHighest expansion depth: 7/40\nExpensive parser function count: 0/500\nUnstrip recursion depth: 0/20\nUnstrip post\u2010expand size: 1174/5000000 bytes\nNumber of Wikibase entities loaded: 0/400\nLua time usage: 0.003/10.000 seconds\nLua memory usage: 525 KB/50 MB\n-->\n<!--\nTransclusion expansion time report (%,ms,calls,template)\n100.00%   24.586      1 Template:Reflist\n100.00%   24.586      1 -total\n  9.77%    2.401      1 Template:Main_other\n-->\n\n<!-- Saved in parser cache with key enwiki:pcache:idhash:29978467-0!canonical and timestamp 20180912092638 and revision id 766248472\n -->\n</div>"},"langlinks":[],"categories":[{"sortkey":"Dif (Technique)","*":"Horticulture_and_gardening"}],"links":[{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Chlorosis"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Greenhouse"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Growing degree-day"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Lilium"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Plant growth regulators"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Plant stem"}],"templates":[{"ns":10,"exists":"","*":"Template:Reflist"},{"ns":10,"exists":"","*":"Template:Main other"},{"ns":828,"exists":"","*":"Module:Check for unknown parameters"}],"images":[],"externallinks":["https://ag.umass.edu/greenhouse-floriculture/fact-sheets/controlling-plant-height-without-chemicals","http://hortservicesinc.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/What-is-DIF.pdf"],"sections":[{"toclevel":1,"level":"2","line":"Basics","number":"1","index